#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Generic obligations gate -- enforces "must do X before Y" rules at the tool layer.

Background: too many "I will always X before Y" verbal commitments evaporate
within the same session because nothing in the harness enforces them. This tool
lets us register a structural gate: an "obligation" is a predicate that must be
true (OR a regex that must NOT match a command) before a particular tool may
fire. PreToolUse hook checks every call; PostToolUse hook auto-satisfies
obligations whose "satisfied_by" pattern matches the tool that just ran.

State: ``~/.config/claude/obligations.json`` (0600), schema:
    {
      "obligations": [
        {
          "id": "ob-YYYY-MM-DD-NNNN",
          "tool_pattern": "Bash" | "Bash:^cat" | "*",
          "exempt_patterns": ["Bash:^watcher-ctl run", "Read"],  # optional
          "predicate": {
            "kind": "file_mtime_within" | "env_present" | "queue_status"
                  | "file_exists" | "no_pipe_pattern" | "marker_file_present"
                  | "watchers_healthy" | "is_main_loop" | "all_of"
                  | ...,
            "params": {...}
          },
          "enforcement": "gate" | "inform",   # default "gate"
          "ttl_secs": 300,
          "expires_at": <unix_ts | null for non-expiring>,
          "created_at": <unix_ts>,
          "created_by": "...",
          "satisfied_by": {
            "tool_pattern": "Bash",
            "command_pattern": "^watcher-ctl run signal-wait-dm"
          } | null,
          "deny_message": "..."
        }
      ],
      "overrides": [
        {
          "id": "ov-YYYY-MM-DD-NNNN",
          "reason": "human-readable why",
          "expires_at": <unix_ts>,
          "created_at": <unix_ts>,
          "created_by": "main-loop"
        }
      ]
    }

Two flavors of "do not block this":

1. **Per-obligation exempt_patterns** (the structural fix). An obligation
   applies iff its ``tool_pattern`` matches AND no entry in
   ``exempt_patterns`` matches. Use to encode "this gate exists but the
   recovery path (e.g. ``watcher-ctl run X``) must always be allowed even
   when the predicate is failing". Exempt-pattern syntax is identical to
   the regular ``tool_pattern`` syntax.

2. **Per-call audited overrides** (the escape hatch). A short-TTL record in
   the ``overrides`` array bypasses ALL gate-mode obligations for the
   duration. Created via ``obligations override <reason> --duration <s>``,
   audited to ``~/.config/claude/obligations-bypass.log``, surfaced in
   ``obligations list``, and self-clears via TTL. Use when you need a
   targeted bypass without permanent harness env-var pollution.

Predicates COMPOSE via the meta-predicate ``all_of`` (and trivially via the
unary ``is_main_loop`` predicate). To express "must be main loop AND <X>",
register ``predicate: {kind: all_of, params: {predicates: [{kind: is_main_loop,
params: {}}, {kind: <X>, params: {...}}]}}``. There is no row-level
``main_loop_only`` flag -- the canonical way to scope an obligation to the
main loop is ``all_of [is_main_loop, ...]``.

Enforcement modes:
  - "gate" (default): PreToolUse hook DENIES the matching tool call when the
        predicate is unsatisfied. The classic obligation: "must do X before Y."
  - "inform": PreToolUse hook NEVER denies. Instead, the PostToolUse hook
        evaluates the predicate after every matching tool call and prints a
        single-line stderr banner if it's unsatisfied. Use for soft surfacing
        ("watcher health is degraded") that should be visible without
        blocking forward progress.

Predicate vocabulary (BOUNDED -- not Turing complete):
  - file_mtime_within: {path, max_age_secs}
        gate is "satisfied" when path's mtime is within max_age_secs of now
  - file_exists: {path, negate?}
        satisfied when path exists (negate=true => satisfied when absent)
  - env_present: {var, value?}
        satisfied when env var is set (and equals value if specified)
  - queue_status: {id, status}
        satisfied when session-task queue item id has the given status
  - no_pipe_pattern: {regex}
        BAN-style predicate: for Bash commands, satisfied when regex does
        NOT match the command string. (Always satisfied for non-Bash tools.)
  - marker_file_present: {path, negate?}
        alias of file_exists for "you owe X" trackers
  - process_alive: {pid_file}
        satisfied when pid_file exists, contains a positive integer, AND
        that PID corresponds to a live process (kill(pid, 0) succeeds).
        Use to enforce "watcher X must actually be running RIGHT NOW" --
        unlike file_mtime_within, this checks process liveness, not file age.
  - process_in_pgrep: {pattern}
        satisfied when `pgrep -f <pattern>` returns at least one PID.
        Use for watchers / processes that don't write a PID file.
  - watchers_healthy: {} (no params)
        satisfied iff `watcher-status --unhealthy-only` produces no output
        (every enabled watcher is `ok`). The "why" string on failure carries
        the unhealthy-watchers report verbatim, so an inform-mode obligation
        using this predicate gives the main loop a concise "X is DOWN"
        banner after every tool call.
  - no_pending_watcher_outputs: {} (no params)
        satisfied iff there are no captured-but-unread watcher outputs.
        Reads sidecars from /tmp/claude-watcher-output-pending/ -- each one
        describes a `watcher-ctl run <name>` background task and the path of
        its captured output file. Predicate fails if any output file has
        been written (size > 0, mtime > registered_at) without yet being
        Read. Auto-cleans stale sidecars (missing output file). Exempts
        Read, Bash:^watcher-ctl, Bash:^(pgrep|pkill|ps), Bash:^cat, and
        Bash:^obligations from the gate to avoid self-deadlock; everything
        else must Read the captured output before proceeding.
  - agent_inbox_empty: {path}
        satisfied iff the JSON inbox at ``path`` is missing OR contains
        no UNREAD messages. Accepts both schema v2 (a dict envelope
        ``{"schema_version": 2, "messages": [...]}``) and legacy v1
        (a bare list of message dicts -- treated as all unread). When
        unread messages are queued, the predicate FAILS and the
        ``why`` field contains a human-readable summary (one line per
        unread entry: from / ts / id / text). Already-read messages
        (``read: true`` in v2) do NOT block the gate -- they remain
        on disk for re-read but are no longer pending work.
        Used by the agent-msg async messaging system: an inform-mode
        obligation registered at agent-spawn time surfaces inbox
        contents to the subagent on the next tool call.
  - stale_ready_queue_present: {threshold_secs?, queue_path?}
        BAN-style predicate: returns True (satisfied = OK) iff NO items in the
        session-task queue are ready_now AND have been waiting >= threshold_secs
        (default 300s = 5 min). Returns False (= deny) when at least one such
        item exists -- the main loop is sitting on a dispatchable item past the
        stale threshold and must dispatch it (or abandon it) before doing
        unrelated work. queue_path defaults to ~/.config/session/queue.json.

        ready_now logic (mirrors session-task `_item_is_ready`): an item is
        ready_now iff status=pending AND it is the group head AND no other
        member of its group is currently running. Group membership is by
        ``group_id`` field. The predicate computes this directly from
        queue.json so it can be evaluated synchronously without shelling
        out to session-task.

        Used by cron-queue-check: when the cron emits a queue-stale-ready
        event, it ALSO registers an obligation with this predicate so the
        gate self-clears once the main loop dispatches (no separate
        post-tool-satisfy needed -- the predicate flips as soon as the
        item leaves ready+pending state).

  - is_main_loop: {negate?}
        satisfied iff the tool call is from the main session loop (i.e. the
        hook payload's ``agent_id`` field is empty/missing). With
        ``negate: true``, satisfied iff inside a subagent (non-empty
        ``agent_id``).

        SCOPE-GUARD ROLE INSIDE all_of: when used as a child of ``all_of``,
        a FAILING ``is_main_loop`` short-circuits the all_of to "inactive"
        (returns satisfied=True from the all_of). Rationale: the natural
        way to express "this obligation only applies in <context>" is to
        AND a scope guard with the actual rule. With strict AND, a
        guard-failed call would propagate False -> deny, which is the
        opposite of "skip the rule when out of scope". So inside all_of,
        ``is_main_loop`` is treated as a precondition gate (also called a
        scope guard or guard clause) rather than a hard predicate. As a
        STANDALONE predicate (not inside all_of), ``is_main_loop`` retains
        its plain-boolean semantics (True iff main loop, optionally
        negated).
  - all_of: {predicates: [predicate, predicate, ...]}
        meta-predicate. Satisfied iff EVERY child predicate is satisfied
        (logical AND), with one short-circuit exception: if any
        ``is_main_loop`` child FAILS, the all_of returns satisfied=True
        ("scope-guard inactive"). The empty list is trivially satisfied.
        The ``why`` string carries the first failing child's diagnostics
        (or the scope-skip note), so the deny banner stays actionable.
        Children are themselves ``{kind, params}`` and may nest
        (``all_of`` inside ``all_of`` is fine, though usually unnecessary).

Subcommands: see argparse below.

Locking: same fcntl.flock pattern as session-task queue.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import argparse
import fcntl
import json
import os
import re
import secrets
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
import time
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path

OBLIGATIONS_FILE = Path.home() / ".config" / "claude" / "obligations.json"

# Sidecar registry for the no_pending_watcher_outputs predicate. Each
# `watcher-ctl run <name>` invocation that runs in the background gets a JSON
# sidecar here describing the captured output file. The PostToolUse hook (in
# post-tool-obligations-update-hook) writes a sidecar when the bg task starts
# and deletes the sidecar when Claude Reads the matching output file. The
# predicate fails for any sidecar whose output file has unread content.
def _watcher_pending_dir() -> Path:
    """Sidecar dir for the no_pending_watcher_outputs predicate. Default
    /tmp/claude-watcher-output-pending/, overridable via the
    WATCHER_PENDING_DIR env var (used by the test suite for isolation)."""
    override = os.environ.get("WATCHER_PENDING_DIR", "").strip()
    if override:
        return Path(override)
    return Path("/tmp/claude-watcher-output-pending")

# Tool/command patterns exempt from the no_pending_watcher_outputs gate.
# Without exemptions the gate would self-deadlock: the gate fires, but every
# tool needed to clear it (Read the output, restart the watcher, diagnose
# with pgrep/ps) would also be blocked. These patterns are checked BEFORE
# the predicate is evaluated -- if any matches, the predicate auto-allows.
#
# Format: list of (tool_pattern, why) tuples. tool_pattern uses the same
# syntax as `_tool_pattern_matches`.
NO_PENDING_WATCHER_OUTPUTS_EXEMPT_PATTERNS = [
    ("Read", "Read is the satisfier -- needed to clear the gate"),
    ("Bash:^watcher-ctl\\b", "watcher-ctl needed to restart the watcher"),
    ("Bash:^(pgrep|pkill|ps)\\b", "process diagnosis"),
    ("Bash:^cat\\b", "alternative read path"),
    ("Bash:^obligations\\b", "obligations CLI needed to inspect/manage gates"),
    # Queue dispatch surface must always work: when several gates fire at
    # once, the recovery action is often "register the running queue item
    # and Read the captured output". Exempt session-task queue + Agent
    # so the loop can always make queue-state progress.
    ("Bash:^session-task\\b",
     "session-task queue dispatch needed for recovery"),
    ("Agent", "spawning subagents is the dispatcher's recovery path"),
]


# UNIVERSAL RECOVERY EXEMPTS: applied to every obligation in `_check_core`
# and `_inform_check_core` BEFORE the predicate is evaluated. These tools
# are the recovery / escape-hatch surface that MUST always work, no matter
# which combination of obligations is currently active.
#
# The deadlock that prompted this list: ob-c834 (no_pending_watcher_outputs)
# and ob-bedb (stale_ready_queue_present) firing simultaneously, where each
# obligation's exempt set was the recovery for the OTHER. The fix is to
# enforce a global recovery floor at the framework level rather than
# trusting every obligation author to remember the union.
#
# CONJUNCTION INVARIANT: obligations form a logical AND -- every active
# obligation must allow a tool call for it to fire. Two obligations whose
# exempt sets do not overlap form a deadlock-in-waiting. The universal
# recovery list below GUARANTEES every obligation has at least the
# escape-hatch surface (`obligations override`, `session-task queue
# register`, Read of watcher-output paths) in its effective exempt set.
#
# Pattern syntax: same as `_tool_pattern_matches`. Patterns are checked
# in `_universal_recovery_exempt_match` and SHORT-CIRCUIT the per-obligation
# evaluation in both gate-mode (_check_core) and inform-mode
# (_inform_check_core).
UNIVERSAL_RECOVERY_EXEMPT_PATTERNS = [
    # The escape hatch itself. `obligations override` MUST always work --
    # it's the documented recovery for any deadlock scenario. Same for
    # satisfy / prune / list / show / check (read-only inspection) and
    # post-tool / inform-check (driven by hooks).
    "Bash:^obligations\\b",
    # Queue dispatch surface. When the main loop is being asked to clear a
    # stale ready item, it MUST be able to call `session-task queue
    # register / spawn-check / done / abandon / promote / set-summary /
    # heartbeat / show / list / banner` and the layer-1 helpers
    # (`session-task set / clear / get`). Listing the leading `session-task`
    # token is enough to cover the entire dispatcher surface.
    "Bash:^session-task\\b",
    # Agent spawn. The dispatcher's primary recovery action is "delegate
    # the queued item to a subagent". Blocking Agent from the main loop
    # means the loop can't dispatch -> the deadlock self-perpetuates.
    "Agent",
    # Watcher recovery surface: when watchers_healthy / process_alive /
    # no_pending_watcher_outputs fire, the recovery is `watcher-ctl run`
    # / `watcher-restart` / `watcher-status`. Always allow.
    "Bash:^watcher-(ctl|status|restart)\\b",
    # Process diagnosis -- needed to figure out which watcher is wedged.
    "Bash:^(pgrep|pkill|ps)\\b",
    # Read of watcher captured-output paths. The pattern matches the
    # ``file_path`` JSON field rendered by _short_command_string for the
    # Read tool: ``{"file_path": "/tmp/claude-1000/.../tasks/<id>.output"}``.
    # We deliberately match by suffix so any watcher captured-output file
    # (regardless of where claude-1000's tmp dir lands) is allowed.
    "Read:tasks/[^\"]+\\.output",
    # Self-clear is the controlled-clear path that frees the loop.
    "Bash:^self-clear\\b",
]

